The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | 7 Indians named in ICC shortlist
                                                                                                                       7                                      7 Indians named in ICC shortlist
            A STAFF REPORTER                      
	Calcutta: The Indian trio of Sachin Tendulkar, Sourav Ganguly and Virender Sehwag have found a place in the list of players nominated for an ICC online poll to pick the all-time greatest team as part of one-day crickets 40th anniversary celebrations.         
	All three are part of the list of openers, from which only two would make the final dream team. Mahendra Singh Dhoni has made it to the list of wicket-keepers. World Cup-winning captain Kapil Dev has found a mention in the all-rounders nomination. Among spinners, Anil Kumble and Harbhajan Singh have made the cut.         
	Shortlist for Dream Team         
	 Openers (2)  Saeed Anwar, Sourav Ganguly, Gordon Greenidge, Matthew Hayden, Sanath Jayasuriya, Virender Sehwag, Sachin Tendulkar, Glenn Turner.         
	 Middle-order batsmen (3)  Michael Bevan, Martin Crowe, Aravinda de Silva, Inzamam-ul Haq, Brian Lara, Javed Miandad, Ricky Ponting, Viv Richards.         
	 All-rounder (1)  Ian Botham, Kapil Dev, Andrew Flintoff, Richard Hadlee, Jacques Kallis, Imran Khan, Lance Klusener, Shaun Pollock.         
	 Wicket-keeper (1)  Mark Boucher, Mahendra Singh Dhoni, Andy Flower Adam Gilchrist, Romesh Kaluwitharana, Moin Khan, Alec Stewart, Kumar Sangakkara.         
	 Fast bowlers (3)  Wasim Akram, Allan Donald, Joel Garner, Michael Holding, Dennis Lillee, Glenn McGrath, Chaminda Vaas, Waqar Younis.         
	 Spinner (1)  Shahid Afridi, Carl Hooper, Anil Kumble, Muttiah Muralidharan, Saqlain Mushtaq, Harbhajan Singh, Shane Warne, Daniel Vettori.         
	Shortlist for greatest ODIs         
	 West Indies bt Australia by 17 runs at Lords, June 21, 1975. India bt WI by 43 runs at Lords, June 25, 1983. Pakistan bt India won by one-wicket at Sharjah, April 18, 1986. England bt Australia by 3 wickets in Sydney, January 22, 1987. Australia bt WI by 1 wicket in Sydney, January 12, 1996. Australia tied with South Africa at Edgbaston, June 17, 1999. Pakistan tied with Sri Lanka, at Sharjah, October 15, 1999. India bt Pakistan by 5 runs in Karachi, March 13, 2004. Bangladesh bt Australia by 5 wickets in Cardiff, June 18, 2005. South Africa bt Australia by 1 wicket in Johannesburg, March 12, 2006.                                                                                                                     
